**Problem:** the approaches(use word replacement,where only one word in the original sentence is replaced with another word to form a sentence pair) remains an outstanding issue.

The paper propose CAT, a novel word-replacement-based approach, whose basic idea is to identify word replacement with controlled impact(referred to as isotopic replacement)

### Related Work

- **Machine Translation Testing:**<br/>
  More approaches focus on **testing the correctness of machine translators**. The major differences lie in the heuristics adopted in these approaches.

  - based on cross-reference:
    - ① checking whether the **direct translation** (from a source language to a target language) and the **indirect translation** (from the source language to an intermediate language and then from the intermediate language to the target language) of the same sentence produce the same results.<br/>
      ② check whether the translation between different translation systems produce the similar translation results.
  - The mainstream approaches test correctness via the combination of input mutation and metamorphic relation 
    - [Testing Machine Translation via Referential Transparency](https://arxiv.org/abs/2004.10361):breaks the original sentence into phrases and checks whether some phrases alone have different translations compared with their translations for the original sentence.
    - **word replacement**: generate a new sentence via replacing one word in the original sentence with another related word.
      - [Structure-Invariant Testing for Machine Translation](https://arxiv.org/pdf/1907.08710.pdf)propose a novel metamorphic testing approach: structure-invariant testing(SIT).SIL adopts the masked language model [(MLM)](https://blog.csdn.net/weixin_51182518/article/details/113929301) to determine which words are likely to fit into the structure of the original sentence.<br/>
        _Note that the word replacement in SIT is primarily syntactical without explicit consideration of semantics,Furthermore, since MLM considers the context of the original sentence when generating the replacement, many syntactically suitable replacements are excluded_
      - [Automatic Testing and Improvement of Machine Translation](https://dl.acm.org/doi/pdf/10.1145/3377811.3380420)
        <img src="data:image/png;base64,"/>
        TransRepair adopts vector representation of words to calculate the similarityof each pair of words. Since the vector representation of each word is calculated on the basis of all sentences containing the word in a corpus, the similarity values between words used in TransRepair do not consider the specific context of the original sentence.



- **Machine Translation Repair:**<br/>
  To repair the revealed bugs and improve machine translation, existing approaches are typically based on [data augmentation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_augmentation).
    - 1.add the generated sentences (noises) used for robustness testing to the training data and retrain the model. 2.used the gradient-based approach to generating sentences for model retraining. 3. designing some additional neural components
    - **TransRepair**: adopts a post processing based strategy for repair. For a bug-revealing sentence, TransRepair generates several similar sentences via the same word replacement strategy in its testing phase; and then combines the translations of these similar sentences and the original sentence to repair the bug.

## Approach

  - Overview
    <img src="data:image/png;base64,"/>
  - Candidate Word Generation<br/>
    Given an input sentence 𝑠, CAT generates such candidate words 𝐶𝑤 by ensuring that each word in𝐶𝑤 is also suitable for the context.This paper use the Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers [(BERT)](https://arxiv.org/pdf/1810.04805.pdf&usg=ALkJrhhzxlCL6yTht2BRmH9atgvKFxHsxQ) to encode the sentence context and check which words are suitable for the context.

     overview of context-aware word replacement in CAT:
    <img src="data:image/png;base64,"/>

     the above procedure for word generation is contextaware, because BERT predicts the masked word based on exactly the remaining parts of the sentence.
    
  - Semantic Evaluation<br/>
    However,there are occasions that BERT predicts a masked word that has similar context with the original word, but with different meanings.Therefore, the paper next compute the **context-aware semantic similarity** and use it to discard the inappropriate words in 𝐶𝑤 for identifying the final word set 𝑊𝑤.
